<DocsLayout title="Writing Your Thesis" toc={toc}>

  <h1>Writing Your Thesis</h1>

  <p>
    Your MSc thesis is more than a graduation requirement — it is your first extended
    piece of scientific writing, a contribution to the lab's knowledge base, and
    (potentially) the seed of a publication. It deserves the same rigour you apply to
    your experiments. This guide covers structure, tools, and practical advice for
    writing a thesis that your committee, co-supervisors, and future lab members will
    actually want to read.
  </p>

  <div class="callout callout-info">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-accent-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <circle cx="12" cy="12" r="10"/><line x1="12" y1="8" x2="12" y2="12"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="16" x2="12.01" y2="16"/>
    </svg>
    <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      The lab provides an official LaTeX template and a PowerPoint presentation template.
      Ask your co-supervisor for the links. Using the templates is mandatory for the final
      submission.
    </p>
  </div>

  <!-- ── Structure ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="structure">Thesis Structure</h2>

  <p>
    A well-structured thesis follows the classic scientific paper pattern, expanded to
    book length. The exact chapter titles and count depend on your work, but the
    underlying logic is universal:
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Chapter</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Typical length</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Introduction</strong></td>
        <td>Motivate the problem, state your research questions, and preview your contributions. A non-expert should understand why this matters after reading this chapter.</td>
        <td>5–10 pages</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Related Work</strong></td>
        <td>Survey prior work in your specific area. Group papers thematically, not chronologically. End each section by explaining what your work does differently.</td>
        <td>10–20 pages</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Background</strong></td>
        <td>Technical preliminaries needed to understand your method (e.g., Transformers, Gaussian Splatting, SLAM). Skip what a PhD student in your area already knows.</td>
        <td>5–15 pages</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Method</strong></td>
        <td>Your contribution. Be precise enough that a skilled reader could re-implement it. Use diagrams liberally.</td>
        <td>15–30 pages</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Experiments</strong></td>
        <td>Experimental setup (datasets, metrics, baselines, hardware), quantitative results, ablation studies, qualitative analysis, and failure cases.</td>
        <td>15–25 pages</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Conclusion</strong></td>
        <td>Summarise contributions, discuss limitations honestly, and propose concrete future directions.</td>
        <td>3–5 pages</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout callout-warning">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-yellow-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <path d="M10.29 3.86L1.82 18a2 2 0 0 0 1.71 3h16.94a2 2 0 0 0 1.71-3L13.71 3.86a2 2 0 0 0-3.42 0z"/>
      <line x1="12" y1="9" x2="12" y2="13"/><line x1="12" y1="17" x2="12.01" y2="17"/>
    </svg>
    <div class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>Start writing early.</strong> Many students leave writing to the last month and
      discover that articulating ideas clearly is significantly harder than implementing them.
      Write rough drafts of each chapter as you complete the corresponding work. Your
      co-supervisor cannot give useful feedback on three years of work in two weeks.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ── LaTeX ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="latex">LaTeX Setup</h2>

  <p>
    All AIRLab theses are written in LaTeX using the official Politecnico di Milano template.
    LaTeX produces typographically superior output for technical documents and handles
    references, equations, and figures far more reliably than word processors.
  </p>

  <h3>Installation</h3>

  <p>
    Install a full TeX distribution locally for writing. Do not rely on Overleaf's
    free tier for a thesis — it times out on large documents.
  </p>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="local machine"
    code={`# macOS
brew install --cask mactex-no-gui

# Ubuntu / Debian
sudo apt install texlive-full latexmk

# Verify installation
pdflatex --version`}
  />

  <h3>Recommended editor</h3>

  <p>
    <a href="https://code.visualstudio.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">VS Code</a>
    with the
    <a href="https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=James-Yu.latex-workshop" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LaTeX Workshop</a>
    extension provides live PDF preview, syntax highlighting, and integration with
    <code>latexmk</code> for continuous compilation.
  </p>

  <h3>Compiling</h3>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="bash"
    filename="thesis root"
    code={`# Compile once (quick check)
pdflatex main.tex

# Full compile with bibliography (run 3 times for cross-references)
latexmk -pdf -interaction=nonstopmode main.tex

# Continuous compilation (watches for file changes)
latexmk -pdf -pvc main.tex

# Clean auxiliary files
latexmk -c`}
  />

