  <!-- ── Writing Advice ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="writing">Writing Advice</h2>

  <p>
    Good scientific writing is clear, precise, and honest. A few principles that most
    thesis students find useful:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <strong>Write for a reader, not for yourself.</strong> Assume the reader is a
      competent engineer or researcher who has not worked on your specific problem.
      Explain why decisions were made, not just what was done.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>One idea per paragraph.</strong> Start each paragraph with a clear
      topic sentence. If a paragraph takes more than 10 lines, it probably contains
      two ideas.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Use active voice.</strong> "We propose a method that…" is stronger
      than "A method is proposed that…". Reserve passive voice for when the agent
      is genuinely unknown or unimportant.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Never copy text from papers without quotation and citation.</strong>
      Paraphrase instead. If you must quote directly, use block quotes with citations.
      Plagiarism — even self-plagiarism from a paper you co-authored — is grounds
      for rejection.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Cite throughout, not only in Related Work.</strong> Every claim about
      prior work anywhere in the thesis needs a citation.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Read your writing aloud.</strong> If it sounds awkward when spoken, it
      needs rewriting. If you need to re-read a sentence twice to understand it, so
      will your committee.
    </li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ── Figures & Tables ────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="figures">Figures & Tables</h2>

  <p>
    A good figure can convey in seconds what a paragraph struggles to say. A bad figure
    confuses the reader and suggests sloppy work. The following rules apply:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Every figure and table must be referenced in the text (<code>\ref&#123;fig:overview&#125;</code>).</li>
    <li>Captions must be self-contained — the reader should understand the figure without reading the surrounding text.</li>
    <li>Use vector graphics (PDF or SVG) for diagrams; PNG/JPEG only for photographs or results that require raster output.</li>
    <li>Use consistent fonts and font sizes across all figures. Match the thesis body font where possible.</li>
    <li>Colour-blind–safe palettes (e.g., <a href="https://colorbrewer2.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ColorBrewer</a>) are strongly preferred.</li>
    <li>Plot error bars or confidence intervals for any quantitative result that involves variance.</li>
  </ul>

  <CodeBlock
    lang="python"
    filename="plot_results.py"
    code={`import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib as mpl

# Match thesis font and use a clean style
mpl.rcParams.update({
    'font.family':    'sans-serif',
    'font.size':      11,
    'axes.linewidth': 0.8,
    'axes.spines.top': False,
    'axes.spines.right': False,
})

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(5, 3.5))
# ... plot your data ...
ax.set_xlabel('Epoch')
ax.set_ylabel('Validation mAP (%)')
ax.legend(frameon=False)

# Export as PDF for lossless embedding in LaTeX
fig.savefig('figures/results.pdf', bbox_inches='tight', dpi=150)`}
  />

  <!-- ── Presentation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="presentation">The Final Presentation</h2>

  <p>
    The thesis defence is typically 20–30 minutes of presentation followed by a
    question-and-answer session with the committee. The official PowerPoint template
    is available from your co-supervisor.
  </p>

  <p>Recommended slide structure:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Slides</th><th>Content</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>1–2</td><td>Title, your name, co-supervisors, lab logo.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>2–4</td><td>Motivation: what problem, why it matters, what was missing.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4–6</td><td>Your approach: architecture diagram or method overview. One key figure.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>6–10</td><td>Results: tables, qualitative examples, ablations. Lead with your strongest result.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>10–11</td><td>Conclusion and future work. Honest about limitations.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Extra</td><td>Backup slides for anticipated questions (implementation details, more ablations, failure cases).</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    Practise the presentation at least twice out loud — once alone, once in front of
    your co-supervisor. Time yourself. A 30-minute slot needs a 22–25 minute
    presentation (leave room for questions within the slot).
  </p>

  <!-- ── Timeline ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────── -->
  <h2 id="timeline">Timeline & Milestones</h2>

  <p>
    A typical 9-month MSc thesis at Polimi follows this approximate schedule. Your
    actual milestones will be set with your co-supervisor.
  </p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Month</th><th>Goal</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>1–2</td><td>Literature review, problem definition, baseline implementation.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>3–4</td><td>Core method development; first draft of Method chapter.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>5–6</td><td>Experiments and ablations; draft Introduction and Related Work.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7</td><td>Complete draft of all chapters; submit to co-supervisor for review.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>8</td><td>Revisions based on feedback; finalise figures and formatting.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>9</td><td>Final submission, presentation preparation, and defence.</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <div class="callout callout-success">
    <svg class="w-5 h-5 flex-shrink-0 mt-0.5 text-green-500" fill="none" stroke="currentColor"
         stroke-width="2" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
      <path d="M22 11.08V12a10 10 0 1 1-5.93-9.14"/>
      <polyline points="22 4 12 14.01 9 11.01"/>
    </svg>
    <div class="text-sm leading-relaxed">
      <strong>The most important advice:</strong> maintain a weekly meeting with your
      co-supervisor throughout the thesis. Show progress — even small progress — at every
      meeting. Problems that go unreported for weeks compound; problems caught early are
      cheap to fix.
    </div>
  </div>

</DocsLayout>
